# Slate Automation

Handle $ARGUMENTS.

Use this when the user wants Codex to work overnight or for many hours on a
Slate v2 surface until it is actually good: correct, fast, visually stable,
well-tested, architecturally clean, and ready for review.

This is a supervisor skill. It does not replace `slate-patch`, `slate-plan`,
`slate-ar-fast`, `slate-ar-stabilize`, `slate-ar-gate`, or `slate-ar-ship`
unless evidence proves the skill topology itself is wrong. It routes them,
repairs missing proof/metrics/skills, reshapes the Slate skill stack when
needed, and keeps the loop honest.

## Core Take

The perfect loop is not "run perf until faster".

The perfect loop is:

```txt
status -> gap scan -> behavior proof -> missing oracle repair -> visual proof
-> benchmark -> patch one hot lane -> verify -> keep/revert -> log -> reassess
```

Repeat by checkpoint, not by giant prompt. One Codex prompt has limited output
and compaction degrades judgment. The supervisor should abuse `autogoal` as the
quality primitive: one focused checkpoint, one durable plan update, one proof
packet, then continue from the checkpoint state instead of relying on chat
scrollback.

Repeat until the surface has no known P0/P1 regressions, meaningful perf is at
target or plateau, visual/editor parity is proven, API/test gaps are closed or
explicitly deferred, decisions are consolidated, and ship readiness is clean.

## Use When

- The user invokes `slate-automation`.
- The user asks to run a long autonomous Slate v2 loop overnight.
- The surface mixes bugs, perf, visual shifts, virtualization, editor behavior,
  missing tests, API cleanup, and workflow repair.
- The user wants "absolute best" implementation quality without picking every
  sub-skill.
- Repeated manual calls to `slate-ar-fast`, `slate-ar-stabilize`, or
  `slate-patch` are producing reactive thrash.

## Do Not Use When

- The user asks one narrow bug fix: use `slate-patch`.
- The user asks one architecture/API plan for review: use `slate-plan`.
- The user asks one benchmark target: use `slate-ar-perf` or `slate-ar-fast`.
- The user asks whether existing gates pass: use `slate-ar-gate`.
- The target is not raw Slate v2 / `.tmp/slate-v2`.

## Invocation Modes

Parse the user's wording into one mode before starting. Record the mode,
timebox, and stop-question policy in the active plan.

- **Full-loop mode:** default when no duration is given. Run one complete
  automation loop until a real stopping checkpoint, completion threshold, or
  ship-readiness boundary. Stop immediately for stop questions.
- **Timed mode:** when the user says `1 hour`, `2 hours`, `overnight`, or a
  similar duration. Run as many safe checkpoint loops as fit the timebox.
  Queue soft stopping checkpoints for final handoff instead of interrupting
  the run, then ask the batch of unblock questions at the end.
- **Batch-loop mode:** when the user says `batch`, `many loops`, `stack
  questions`, or wants to unblock everything at the end. Behaves like timed
  mode even without an explicit duration: keep working through safe alternate
  owners and stack soft stopping checkpoints for final handoff.

Natural prompts should work:

- `slate-automation pagination rows800 virtualized`
- `slate-automation pagination rows800 virtualized full loop`
- `slate-automation pagination rows800 virtualized for 1 hour`
- `slate-automation huge-document auto timed 2h`
- `slate-automation editor behavior batch loop`

For timed and batch-loop modes:

- calculate or record the timebox before mutable work;
- do not start a risky patch that cannot be verified inside the remaining time;
- finish or quarantine the current packet before handoff;
- keep queued stop questions concise and answerable in one pass;
- after the user answers the batch, first apply reusable taste captures and
  plan decisions, then resume queued packets.

## Goal Contract

Use `autogoal` aggressively. It is the supervisor's memory, checkpoint,
anti-compaction strategy, and quality gate.

Goal handle shape:

```txt
Automate <surface>; done when behavior, visual, perf, repair, docs, and ship-readiness gates pass; plan docs/plans/<path>.md.
```

The plan must record:

- surface and target route/package;
- invocation mode, timebox, and deadline when present;
- completion threshold;
- behavior families in scope;
- visual proof surface;
- primary perf metric and correctness contract;
- API/DX cleanup authority;
- benchmark/test/skill repair authority;
- docs consolidation target;
- north-star profile read/update state;
- taste coverage gaps and capture state;
- packet ledger location;
- changed-list location;
- review-attention list location;
- queued stopping-checkpoint list location;
- workflow-slowdown ledger location;
- stop rules and blockers.

Use `--template task --with browser --with package-api --with agent-native`
when browser/package/skill surfaces are in play.

## Autogoal Checkpoint Model

Do not run an overnight task as one huge assistant turn.

Split long work into checkpoints that fit one high-quality prompt:

- **Taste checkpoint:** read
  the `slate-north-star` skill as checkpoint zero, then read the active goal
  plan and latest user request. If the north-star profile is missing or stale
  for a reusable decision, consolidate it before patching.
- **Taste-capture checkpoint:** stop implementation when the next safe move
  depends on user taste that `slate-north-star` does not cover. Record the
  taste gap in the plan, ask at most one terse checkpoint question only when
  the answer is genuinely missing, then patch `slate-north-star` from the
  answer before resuming. In timed or batch-loop mode, queue the question when
  safe alternate work remains.
- **Status checkpoint:** read current goal, plan, AR status, dirty evidence, and
  latest user request.
- **Proof checkpoint:** run one behavior/visual/package/browser gate family and
  record pass/fail signatures.
- **Patch checkpoint:** fix one correctness class or one missing oracle.
- **Perf checkpoint:** optimize one measured hot lane with correctness green.
- **Architecture checkpoint:** run `slate-plan` only when the next safe win is a
  public/internal API or runtime boundary.
- **Skill-repair checkpoint:** patch the owning skill/rule when the workflow
  missed a recurring expectation.
- **Workflow-slowdown checkpoint:** when a specialist command, gate, review,
  finalizer, browser proof, or benchmark burns unexpected time, log the slow
  step and repair the owning workflow if the slowdown is avoidable or repeated.
- **Consolidation checkpoint:** move accepted reusable decisions into durable
  docs/rules before ship readiness.
- **Changed-list checkpoint:** update the concise list of all current-run
  changes before final handoff so the user does not need to read every diff.
- **Review-attention checkpoint:** rank the few things that most need user
  attention before final handoff.
- **Stopping-checkpoint queue:** in timed or batch-loop mode, collect soft
  blockers and user-answer checkpoints for final handoff instead of stopping
  immediately when safe alternate work remains.
- **Ship checkpoint:** run `slate-ar-ship` readiness and pause only for
  explicit commit/PR authority.

Each checkpoint must end with:

- plan state updated;
- evidence recorded with cwd/tool;
- packet ledger row for any code, test, benchmark, docs, or skill packet;
- workflow-slowdown row when a checkpoint, command, or specialist step is
  materially slower than expected;
- changed-list row when files, commands, docs, tests, benchmarks, examples, or
  skills changed;
- review-attention row when a packet needs human review, taste confirmation,
  risky API attention, or close visual inspection;
- queued stopping-checkpoint row for any deferred question or user decision;
- next checkpoint owner named;
- `check-complete.mjs` run only when the whole goal is actually closable.

If output starts getting large, stop expanding prose and write artifacts or plan
rows. The next activation should resume from the goal plan, not from compacted
chat.

## Packet Ledger

Every optimization, bug fix, oracle repair, benchmark repair, docs repair, or
skill repair is a packet. The active goal plan must carry a compact ledger with
one row per packet:

- packet id and checkpoint owner;
- hypothesis or failure signature;
- files/commands changed or inspected;
- baseline, latest, and best metric when a metric exists;
- behavior proof and visual proof run;
- decision: `keep`, `revert`, or `quarantine`;
- reason for that decision;
- next owner or follow-up.

Use the decisions strictly:

- `keep` only when correctness, native editor behavior, visual proof, and any
  relevant metric are green enough for the packet's risk.
- `revert` when the packet creates a known regression, hides latency behind
  fake debounce, dirties API shape without architectural approval, or has no
  credible proof.
- `quarantine` when the packet contains useful evidence or partial code but is
  not shippable. Quarantined packets do not count toward completion, ship
  readiness, or benchmark wins until promoted to `keep`.

No-code proof packets still get a ledger row with pass/fail evidence and the
next owner. A final handoff without packet decisions is incomplete.

## Workflow Slowdown Ledger

Automation performance is part of product quality. Slow agent loops hide real
work, waste timeboxes, and make overnight runs harder to trust.

Log a workflow-slowdown row when:

- a checkpoint takes materially longer than expected;
- a specialist skill spends time on avoidable setup, broad scans, repeated
  finalization, redundant gates, or noisy output;
- a command has no narrow mode and blocks timed/batch progress;
- `slate-ar-ship`, finalization, `autoreview`, browser proof, or benchmark
  setup dominates the loop without producing proportional evidence;
- compaction/output budget pressure is caused by command shape rather than the
  real task.

Each row must include:

- step or command;
- owner skill/script/package;
- elapsed time or best available estimate;
- expected timebox if known;
- why it was slow;
- evidence produced;
- repair decision: keep as necessary, narrow command, cache/reuse evidence,
  split checkpoint, patch skill, patch script, or defer with reason.

Repair repeated or avoidable workflow slowdowns:

- slow specialist routing -> patch the owning `.agents/rules/slate-*.mdc`;
- slow finalization/readiness -> patch `slate-ar-ship` or
  `slate-ar-finalize`;
- slow proof gate -> add a focused gate or route through `slate-ar-gate`;
- slow browser repetition -> promote reusable proof into `slate-browser`;
- slow benchmark setup -> fix benchmark target/script ergonomics;
- slow output -> narrow command output or write artifacts instead of streaming.

Do not optimize away necessary proof. A slow step is acceptable when it is the
only honest evidence for the claim, but the handoff must say so.

## Taste Coverage Stop

`slate-north-star` is the supervisor's taste profile. If the loop reaches a
stopping checkpoint, user-answer checkpoint, or architecture decision and the
needed preference is not covered there, stop implementation before more product
or runtime work.

Record a taste-gap row in the active plan:

- prompt or stopping checkpoint that exposed the gap;
- missing preference or decision pressure;
- exact user answer when available;
- reusable rule candidate;
- owner: `slate-north-star`, another `.agents/rules/**` file, or non-reusable
  run note;
- capture decision: `recorded`, `not reusable`, or `needs one answer`.

When the user answers a stopping checkpoint and the answer is reusable, first
patch `.agents/rules/slate-north-star.mdc`, run `pnpm install`, verify the
generated skill mirror with `rg`, and then resume the automation. If the answer
is run-specific, record it in the active plan and mark the taste gap
`not reusable`.

Do not turn this into routine polling. Ask only when the answer changes product
intent, risk tolerance, architecture ownership, or a taste rule that cannot be
inferred from source evidence. Do not ship while reusable taste gaps remain
uncaptured.

## Stopping Checkpoint Queue

Timed and batch-loop modes do not stop at the first soft question. They stack
questions for the final handoff when another safe owner remains runnable.

Queue soft checkpoints:

- missing taste rule where work can continue on unrelated safe packets;
- user-only product preference for one packet while other packets remain safe;
- architecture/API fork that affects one lane but does not block proof, docs,
  benchmark, skill, or oracle repair elsewhere;
- scoped proof limitation that needs user claim-width confirmation;
- accepted deferral that deserves final review.

Never defer hard checkpoints:

- commit, push, PR, branch creation, destructive cleanup, or external
  credential;
- unsafe API/runtime break where no safe alternate work remains;
- same real blocker repeated with no autonomous move left;
- tool/access failure that prevents all meaningful progress;
- explicit user instruction to stop at the first checkpoint;
- timebox expired with an unfinished risky packet.

Each queued stopping checkpoint needs:

- id;
- type: taste, product, API/runtime, proof-width, deferral, authority, or other;
- question or needed decision;
- why the decision matters;
- what work was paused or skipped;
- what safe work continued;
- current recommendation;
- exact file, route, command, benchmark, screenshot, or plan row anchor.

Final handoff must group queued questions so the user can answer them in one
reply. After the user answers, update the plan, capture reusable taste in
`slate-north-star`, and resume the highest-value queued owner first.

## Changed List Checkpoint

Autogoal-backed Slate automation must leave a readable list of what changed.
The active plan and final handoff must include a concise current-run list,
derived from the packet ledger and current file/source evidence, not old branch
history.

Group it like this:

- code/runtime/API;
- tests/oracles/browser proof;
- benchmarks/metrics/targets;
- examples/docs;
- skills/workflow;
- reverted/quarantined packets.

Keep each row short and concrete. Include only things changed or intentionally
reverted/quarantined during the current automation run. If a group has no
changes, say `none`. No public changelog prose.

## Review Attention Checkpoint

The final handoff must include the items that most deserve the user's attention.
This is not another changed-list. It is a ranked review guide.

Include at most five items, ordered by review value:

- risky architecture/API decision;
- behavior that passed tests but still deserves human visual feel;
- perf tradeoff or plateau that affects product judgment;
- quarantined packet or accepted deferral;
- changed skill/workflow rule that alters future automation behavior;
- area where browser proof is scoped narrower than the user's likely claim.

Each item must say:

- what to inspect;
- why it matters;
- exact file, route, command, screenshot, benchmark, or plan row to inspect;
- current agent recommendation: accept, inspect closely, defer, or reject.

If there is nothing meaningful for the user to review, say `none`, but only
after checking packet ledger decisions, scoped proof, residual risks, and
changed workflow rules.

## No Runtime Questions

Do not pause for routine "grill me" questions during the loop.

The supervisor self-grills:

- What would the user complain about after watching the route for 30 seconds?
- What native editor behavior could this patch break?
- What visual shift or blank state would not show in metrics?
- Is the benchmark measuring the real editor operation or hiding the hot lane?
- Is this a package/runtime API smell rather than another route patch?
- Did a skill miss a recurring expectation that should be repaired?
- What decision should be consolidated so the next run does not rediscover it?

Answer these from code, tests, docs, Browser, screenshots, Playwright, and
benchmarks. Stop only for a true authority boundary:

- commit, push, PR, branch creation, destructive cleanup, external credential,
  or a user-only product decision;
- an unsafe API break where the repo evidence leaves two viable futures and the
  wrong choice would be expensive.

Do not ask one question per packet. If a boundary question is unavoidable,
record the blocked state once with the exact decision needed. In timed or
batch-loop mode, queue soft questions and keep working on safe alternate owners.

## Authority

The supervisor may repair workflow sources when the loop proves they are wrong.
It may also change the Slate skill topology when overlap, missing ownership, or
stale routing is causing repeated misses.

Allowed skill repair:

1. identify the missed recurring expectation;
2. patch the owning `.agents/rules/<owner>.mdc`;
3. run `pnpm install` to sync generated `.agents/skills/**/SKILL.md`;
4. verify source and generated mirror with `rg`;
5. record the repair in the goal plan.

Use `slate-patch repair <expectation>` for patch-lane misses.
Use `autogoal repair <expectation>` for universal goal lifecycle misses.
Patch `slate-automation` itself when the supervisor cadence, proof, or routing
missed the expectation.

Allowed topology changes:

- update any `.agents/rules/slate-*.mdc` rule;
- create a new `slate-*` skill when a repeated workflow has no clear owner;
- merge skills when two wrappers overlap and confuse routing;
- remove or deprecate a `slate-*` skill when it adds ceremony without distinct
  ownership;
- update `argument-hint`, description, routing, stop rules, and handoff shape;
- update benchmark target policy and proof-gate ownership when needed.

Topology changes need evidence:

- repeated miss, routing confusion, or no-owner gap;
- source-rule patch, not generated mirror edits;
- `pnpm install`;
- generated mirror audit with `rg`;
- agent-native review;
- plan row explaining what future mistake is now prevented.

Do not hand-edit generated `.agents/skills/**/SKILL.md`.

## Learning Loop

Every failed attempt is classified before the next checkpoint:

- runtime bug;
- missing oracle;
- missing metric;
- lying metric;
- weak visual proof;
- stale docs/decision memory;
- bad public/internal API shape;
- missing taste coverage;
- wrong specialist owner;
- missing skill;
- overlapping/dead skill;
- workflow slowdown;
- too-large prompt/output-budget miss.

Then repair the owning layer:

- runtime bug -> `slate-patch`;
- missing oracle -> `slate-patch` or `tdd`;
- missing/lying metric -> benchmark target/script repair;
- visual proof gap -> Browser/screenshot/Playwright geometry proof;
- stale docs -> decision consolidation;
- bad API -> `slate-plan` or accepted implementation;
- missing taste coverage -> stop, capture the answer, and patch
  `slate-north-star` before resuming when the answer is reusable;
- wrong/missing/overlapping skill -> `.agents/rules/**` repair;
- workflow slowdown -> log the slow owner, then patch the skill, script, gate,
  command shape, or checkpoint split when the slowdown is avoidable;
- output-budget miss -> split into smaller autogoal checkpoint.

Learning is only real when the future loop changes. A plan note without a rule,
test, metric, doc, or owner update is just archaeology.

## Cadence

Each loop cycle has one primary owner and one packet-ledger decision.

1. **Status:** run `slate-ar-status` or direct source/status reads.
2. **Quality gap:** run `slate-ar-quality` when API, DX, test, docs, or metric
   coverage is unclear.
3. **Behavior:** run `slate-ar-stabilize` / `slate-ar-gate` before perf.
4. **Oracle repair:** if proof is missing, use `slate-patch` or `tdd`.
5. **Vision proof:** use Browser, screenshot, and/or Playwright geometry checks
   for visual/editor parity.
6. **Perf:** run `slate-ar-fast` / `slate-ar-perf` only with correctness green.
7. **API cleanup:** use `slate-plan` when repeated bugs show bad public or
   internal API shape.
8. **Skill repair:** patch source rules when the loop itself missed policy.
9. **Decision consolidation:** update durable docs before ship readiness.
10. **Ship readiness:** use `slate-ar-ship` when the current tree is reviewable.

After each cycle:

- keep only if correctness and visual proof are green enough for the packet's
  risk;
- revert, rework, or quarantine if the packet weakens behavior, hides work
  behind debounce, breaks native editor expectations, or makes API shape
  dirtier;
- switch bottleneck after two correctness-green no-gain packets;
- route to `slate-plan` when the next win is architectural;
- log evidence, rejected attempts, and the next owner in the plan.

## Taste Profile

Act like the user would after reading the code at 2am:

- long-term architecture over local symptom patches;
- package/runtime owner over example glue;
- no hidden debounce wins unless explicitly accepted;
- no fake stress fixtures pretending to be realistic docs;
- examples should show the actual API/DX, not helper ceremony;
- source of truth first, generated mirrors second;
- no branch/review-branch surprises;
- no public changelog prose in internal decision docs;
- no "green" claim without behavior, visual, and metric truth matching the
  surface;
- delete, merge, or repair workflow tools when they confuse ownership.

## Vision Proof

Metrics are not enough. Browser-visible editor work needs a human-like proof.

Use the in-app Browser for live local routes when a route is named or obvious.
Use Playwright for replayable proof. Use screenshots or geometry assertions when
the failure can be visual:

- text shifts on selection/focus;
- blank virtualized windows;
- overlapped pages/content;
- wrong scroll anchoring;
- caret at the wrong visual line;
- margin click placed on the wrong side;
- table/page fragment drift;
- native selection handles not matching model selection.

For route-level editor proof, simulate real use:

- click paragraph, table cell, margin, page corner;
- type bursts and Enter bursts;
- double click word;
- drag selection across lines and pages;
- undo/redo after edits;
- copy/paste/select-all where relevant;
- scroll away and back, then continue typing;
- strategy/control changes when the example exposes them.

Classify intentionally skipped families in the plan. Do not claim full editor
parity when only one route and one gesture were checked.

## Scenario Generator

Before route-level proof, synthesize a scenario matrix from the named surface
instead of checking random gestures.

Build rows from these axes:

- document topology: paragraphs, wrapped text, lists, tables, voids, pages,
  blank space, hidden/materialized blocks, and huge-doc windows present on the
  route;
- viewport and strategy: staged, virtualized, auto, rows/count controls,
  desktop/mobile where relevant, top/middle/end scroll positions;
- editor gesture: click, double click, drag selection, margin click, arrow nav,
  type burst, Enter burst, paste, select-all, undo/redo, scroll away/back;
- assertion family: model selection, DOM selection, caret rect, scroll anchor,
  visible text, DOM node budget, type-to-paint, console errors, and screenshot
  or pixel/geometry stability;
- native parity risk: browser behavior that should remain native unless Slate
  deliberately owns it.

Pick the smallest matrix that covers the surface risk, then expand when a bug
appears. Add new rows when user reports, screenshots, or Browser observation
show a missed human journey. Promote repeated rows into reusable Playwright or
`slate-browser` helpers instead of retyping the same automation.

## Repair Duties

The supervisor repairs whatever layer is missing:

- **Bug:** reproduce and fix with `slate-patch`.
- **Missing oracle:** add Playwright/unit/Browser proof with `slate-patch` or
  `tdd`.
- **Missing metric:** update `benchmarks/targets/slate-v2.json`, benchmark
  script, and `METRIC` output before optimizing.
- **Lying metric:** fix summary/worst-lane math before using it as a gate.
- **Weak example DX:** improve the example only when it is the API contract
  surface; otherwise fix package/runtime ownership.
- **API smell:** use `slate-plan` or implement the accepted shape when the plan
  is already accepted.
- **Missing taste coverage:** stop at the checkpoint, record the missing taste
  in the plan, capture the user's answer, and patch `slate-north-star` when
  reusable.
- **Repeated browser proof pattern:** promote it into the `slate-browser` API,
  helper commands, or proof contract so future agents can run it directly.
- **Workflow slowdown:** log slow commands/checkpoints, classify the owner, and
  repair avoidable slow paths in the owning skill, script, proof gate, or
  benchmark command.
- **Skill miss:** patch `.agents/rules/**`, sync, and verify generated mirrors.
- **Docs memory gap:** consolidate accepted decisions into durable docs.

## Decision Consolidation

Before closeout, consolidate decisions so the next overnight run does not
rediscover them.

At the start of a long run, ingest decisions before acting:

- read the `slate-north-star` skill first;
- search active/recent goal plans under `docs/plans/**`;
- search accepted architecture/proof docs under `docs/slate-v2/**`;
- search compiled evidence under `docs/research/**`;
- read benchmark target context from `benchmarks/targets/slate-v2.json`;
- read source rules for any specialist skill before blaming the specialist.

At every stop or handoff, compare the reason against `slate-north-star`. If the
user's preference is missing and reusable, update `slate-north-star` before
claiming the automation loop is ready to resume or ship.

Use the smallest durable target:

- active goal plan for run-specific findings;
- `slate-north-star` for reusable user taste, correction patterns, and
  supervisor routing decisions;
- `docs/slate-v2/**` for accepted Slate v2 architecture, proof, issue, and
  reviewer-facing decisions;
- `docs/research/**` only for research/evidence layers;
- `.agents/rules/**` only for reusable agent workflow policy.

Do not write public changelog prose. Write latest-state decisions, proof
commands, accepted tradeoffs, rejected alternatives, and next owner.

For "think like me" work, create or update a compact north-star decision doc
only after decisions are accepted and reusable. Do not dump raw chat history
into the skill. The skill should know where to search and what to consolidate,
not carry every decision in its own body.

When the task is to improve the north-star profile itself, use numbered
source-read passes over the owner docs instead of a vague docs review. Record
the pass count, source families, reusable gaps found, and resulting profile
changes in the active goal plan.

If the user specifies a batch shape, obey it exactly. For example, "10
iterations reading docs/ 10 files at a time" means ten concrete checkpoints,
each with ten explicit `docs/**` file paths read and logged before synthesis.
Do not substitute thematic source-family passes, directory summaries, or a
single broad scan for a requested file-batched pass.

## Stop Rules

Stop when:

- completion threshold passes;
- ship/readiness path says `READY TO COMMIT` or asks for explicit commit/PR
  approval;
- `slate-north-star` does not cover a taste or risk-tolerance decision needed
  for the next safe move and no safe alternate owner remains, or the invocation
  mode is full-loop;
- the next safe move is a `slate-plan` public API/runtime decision;
- a same-signal behavior failure has already been routed through the right
  specialist owner and still needs a user-only decision or unsafe architecture
  choice;
- the same real blocker repeats and no autonomous move remains.
- the timed/batch timebox expires after the current packet is verified, reverted,
  or quarantined.

Do not stop just because one benchmark improved or one focused test passed.
Do not stop just because a behavior lane needs `slate-patch`; switch owner
inside the same automation loop and keep the packet ledger honest.
When stopping for missing taste, record the gap and resume by updating
`slate-north-star` from the user's answer before more implementation.
In timed or batch-loop mode, prefer queuing soft stopping checkpoints over
stopping early when safe, high-value work remains.

## Final Handoff

Report:

- goal plan path;
- surface and route/package;
- invocation mode, elapsed time/timebox when relevant, and loop/checkpoint
  count;
- behavior gates and visual proof run;
- primary metric baseline/latest/best and stop reason;
- bugs fixed and oracles added;
- benchmark/skill/docs repairs made;
- workflow slowdown rows and repairs, including slow-but-necessary proof;
- concise changed list grouped by code, tests/oracles, benchmarks, examples/docs,
  skills/workflow, and reverted/quarantined packets;
- `Needs your attention` section with the highest-review-value items, each with
  file/route/command anchor and recommendation;
- `Stopping checkpoints to unblock` section with queued questions, current
  recommendation, and exact anchors;
- accepted deferrals and residual risks;
- next owner: continue automation, `slate-plan`, `slate-ar-ship`, or blocked
  authority decision.
